---
import LocationLayout from '../../layouts/LocationLayout.astro';
import { marsLocations } from '../../data/marsLocations';

const location = marsLocations.find(loc => loc.id === 'medusae-fossae');
if (!location) {
  throw new Error('Medusae Fossae Formation location not found');
}
---

<LocationLayout title="Medusae Fossae Formation - Mars Location" location={location}>
  <!-- Hero Image Section -->
  <div class="mb-8">
    <div
      class="relative h-96 bg-gradient-to-r from-orange-900 to-red-700 rounded-lg overflow-hidden"
    >
      <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-black/20"></div>
      <div class="absolute bottom-6 left-6 text-white">
        <p class="text-sm opacity-80">
          Mars Express radar view of layered deposits in Medusae Fossae Formation
        </p>
        <p class="text-xs opacity-60">ESA/Mars Express/MARSIS</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Overview Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">Overview</h2>
    <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-3 gap-8">
      <div class="lg:col-span-2">
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          The Medusae Fossae Formation (MFF) stands as one of Mars' most enigmatic 
          geological features, extending discontinuously for over 5,000 kilometers 
          along the planet's equator. This massive deposit, covering an area equal 
          to 20% the size of the continental United States, represents the largest 
          source of dust on Mars and potentially one of its most significant water 
          ice reservoirs.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Recent 2024 discoveries have revolutionized our understanding of the MFF, 
          revealing extensive water ice deposits beneath its surface that could 
          cover the entire planet in an ocean 1.5 to 2.7 meters deep if melted. 
          This finding transforms the formation from a simple dust source into a 
          potential treasure trove of resources for future Mars exploration.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          The formation's easily eroded volcanic ash and dust composition has 
          played a crucial role in shaping Mars' global atmosphere and climate, 
          while its buried ice deposits suggest complex geological processes 
          involving both volcanic activity and water ice accumulation over 
          billions of years.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Quick Facts Sidebar -->
      <div class="bg-gray-800/50 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">Quick Facts</h3>
        <div class="space-y-3">
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Length:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">5,000+ km</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Area:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">20% of continental US</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Ice Thickness:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">Up to 3.7 km deep</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Composition:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">Volcanic ash, dust, water ice</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Age:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">Amazonian period</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Formation and Origins Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Formation and Volcanic Origins
    </h2>
    <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-8 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        The Medusae Fossae Formation is composed of weakly cemented particles, 
        most likely formed by massive volcanic ash deposits from pyroclastic 
        flows or similar explosive volcanic activity. These materials were 
        deposited over extensive periods during Mars' Amazonian era, creating 
        one of the largest sedimentary formations on the planet.
      </p>
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Volcanic Sources</h4>
          <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
            Recent research suggests multiple volcanic sources contributed to the 
            MFF, including ash from Olympus Mons, Apollinaris Mons, Arsia Mons, 
            and Pavonis Mons. The formation may have originated from pumice rafts 
            and massive explosive eruptions that distributed ash across vast 
            equatorial regions.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Dust Production</h4>
          <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
            The MFF's easily eroded nature makes it the single largest source 
            of dust on Mars. Its chemical composition, rich in sulfur and 
            chlorine, provides the best match to global Martian dust measurements, 
            confirming its role as the primary contributor to Mars' dusty atmosphere.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 2024 Breakthrough Discoveries Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      2024 Breakthrough: Hidden Water Ice Reservoirs
    </h2>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-1 gap-6 mb-8">
      <div
        class="bg-gradient-to-br from-blue-900/50 to-cyan-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-blue-700/50"
      >
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Massive Subsurface Ice Discovery
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">
          Using updated data from Mars Express's MARSIS radar, scientists discovered 
          extensive layered deposits of water ice beneath the MFF, reaching depths 
          of up to 3.7 kilometers. These deposits are protected by a layer of dry 
          dust or ash several hundred meters thick, preserving them from sublimation.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
          If all the suspected water ice in the formation melted, it would create 
          a global ocean covering Mars to a depth of 1.5 to 2.7 meters - making 
          it one of the largest water reservoirs on the planet outside the polar caps.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
        Implications for Mars Exploration
      </h3>
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        This discovery fundamentally changes our understanding of water distribution 
        on Mars. The MFF's equatorial location makes it far more accessible than 
        polar ice caps, potentially providing a crucial water source for future 
        human missions and settlements.
      </p>
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
        The protective dust layer above the ice suggests that these deposits could 
        remain stable over geological timescales, offering a reliable and accessible 
        water resource for in-situ resource utilization (ISRU) activities.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Dust Source Significance Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Mars' Primary Dust Factory
    </h2>
    <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-3 gap-6">
      <div class="lg:col-span-2">
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          The Medusae Fossae Formation plays a crucial role in Mars' atmospheric 
          dynamics as the planet's largest dust source. Long-term deflation and 
          erosion of the formation have significantly contributed to the global 
          Martian dust reservoir that creates the planet's characteristic dusty 
          atmosphere and global dust storms.
        </p>

        <div class="space-y-4 mb-6">
          <div class="border-l-4 border-orange-500 pl-4">
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">
              Chemical Fingerprint
            </h4>
            <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
              The MFF has the highest abundance of sulfur and chlorine compounds, 
              providing the best chemical match to surface measurements of Martian dust.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">
              Global Distribution
            </h4>
            <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
              Volume estimates suggest that eroded materials from the MFF have 
              distributed dust across the entire planet through atmospheric transport.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="border-l-4 border-yellow-500 pl-4">
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">
              Climate Impact
            </h4>
            <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
              The continuous dust production affects Mars' radiation balance, 
              atmospheric opacity, and seasonal weather patterns.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-800/50 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
